      <div class="prose">

        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>The most common reason construction software investments fail to deliver ROI isn't the software — it's the implementation. Platforms get purchased, licenses get assigned, and then the software sits largely unused because the team wasn't trained properly, adoption wasn't enforced, or the workflows were never configured for how the company actually operates.</p>

        <p>This guide walks through a six-step onboarding process that maximizes the probability of successful adoption.</p>

        <h2>Why construction software implementations fail</h2>
        <p>Before the steps, understand what you're guarding against:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No champion:</strong> Nobody owns the implementation. Everyone uses it sporadically; nobody uses it fully</li>
          <li><strong>Big bang launch:</strong> All features activated for all projects at once — overwhelming for teams already under project pressure</li>
          <li><strong>Training without follow-through:</strong> One training session, then abandoned when it gets hard</li>
          <li><strong>Failure to configure:</strong> Using the software in its default state instead of setting it up to match your actual workflows</li>
          <li><strong>No executive enforcement:</strong> If the owner or PM doesn't use it, nobody else will</li>
          <li><strong>Old systems run in parallel:</strong> Teams keep using spreadsheets "just in case," which means data lives in two places and neither is reliable</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 1: Name an implementation champion</h2>
        <p>Every successful construction software implementation has one person who owns it. This person:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Leads the configuration and setup process</li>
          <li>Conducts or coordinates training</li>
          <li>Answers team questions in the first 60 days</li>
          <li>Escalates to the vendor when issues arise</li>
          <li>Reports adoption metrics to ownership</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This is typically the most tech-comfortable project manager, office manager, or in some smaller companies, the owner themselves. Without a champion, implementation is nobody's job — which means it doesn't happen.</p>

        <h2>Step 2: Configure before launch</h2>
        <p>The biggest time investment in onboarding is setup — getting the platform configured to match your actual business before anyone starts using it for real work. Key configuration items depend on the platform but typically include:</p>

        <h3>Cost codes and budget structure</h3>
        <p>Your cost codes should match your estimating and accounting system. If you track labor, materials, subs, and overhead in four categories, configure four. If you use 30 detailed cost codes that match your QuickBooks chart of accounts, configure all 30. This is tedious but essential — fixing cost codes after projects are in progress creates a data mess.</p>

        <h3>Schedule templates</h3>
        <p>Create Gantt schedule templates for your typical project types. A custom home might have 50 scheduled tasks; a bathroom remodel might have 15. Build the templates once, then deploy for each new project. Don't start from scratch on every project.</p>

        <h3>Estimating templates and cost catalog</h3>
        <p>Import your standard estimating line items and historical pricing into the platform's cost catalog. This is the setup that pays dividends on every estimate you build afterward.</p>

        <h3>User roles and permissions</h3>
        <p>Configure what each role can see and do: owners see everything; project managers see their projects; subs see only what they need; clients see what you want them to see. Default permission settings are rarely right for any specific company.</p>

        <h3>Integrations</h3>
        <p>Set up QuickBooks or accounting integration before the first financial transaction. Setting up integrations retroactively after projects are running is significantly more complex.</p>

